		<h1>About VIVO</h1>

			<h2><Strong>What is VIVO?</strong></h2>

				<ul class="answers">
					<li>VIVO is an open, on-line interlinked collection of data and tools for research discovery and scholarship. VIVO represents information about scholars and scholarship--people, grants, scholarly work, resources, events, interests, activities and accomplishments--and their interconnections.

					<li>VIVO is a powerful search tool for precisely locating people, grants, publications, and more.

					<li>The VIVO project is funded by the National Institutes of Health, U24 RR029822, "VIVO: Enabling National Networking of Scientists."

				</ul>

			<h2><strong>Why is this called VIVO?</strong></h2>

				<p>The term "VIVO" is a reference to the term "<em>in vivo</em>," Latin for "within the living." The name was developed at Cornell University in 2003 and seems appropriate for a system devoted to the living, breathing world of research and scholarship.

			<h2><strong>What are the key benefits of VIVO?</strong></h2>

				<ul class="answers">
					<li>VIVO provides information regarding grants, research, resources, publications, and people, enabling research discovery across UF and participating institutions.

					<li>VIVO data is largely obtained using automated methods from public, authoritative sources within and outside an institution. This reduces the effort for faculty and staff to gather and provide data.

					<li>VIVO's search is faceted. This means that if searching for people, you will get a list of people. If searching for grants, you will get a list of grants.

					<li>VIVO information is linked. This means that you can follow links in VIVO from a person to a grant for that person, to other people who work on the same grant, to the department administering the grant, to people in that department, to publications of people in that department, etc. VIVO creates opportunities for open discovery of research connections by following these links.

				</ul>
					
			<h2><strong>Why should I use VIVO?</strong></h2>

				<ul class="answers">
					<li>VIVO is useful for researchers seeking collaborators on inter-disciplinary proposals.

					<li>VIVO can connect multi-disciplinary research groups within an institution.

					<li>VIVO enables promotion of upcoming research and presentations.

					<li>VIVO allows researchers to showcase their credentials.

					<li>Students can use VIVO to search for graduate study mentors and programs.

					<li>VIVO assists research offices in finding researchers with specialized skills or expertise.

					<li>VIVO can showcase faculty and departmental activities.
	
					<li>VIVO can help people find experts for review panels, symposia, etc.

					<li>VIVO can help researchers find research labs, facilities, and other research resources.

					<li>VIVO provides information regarding grant activity at the investigator and unit levels.

					<li>VIVO's cross-linked data ensures that VIVO is not only highly searchable, but also browseable, intuitive in design, and user friendly.

				</ul>

			<h2><strong>Who are the primary users of VIVO?</strong></h2>

				<p>Researchers, scholars, students, librarians, administrators, funding agencies, donors, and members of the general public may all benefit from utilizing VIVO. </p>

			<h2><strong>Can I link my VIVO profile to my personal web page?</strong></h2>

				<p>Yes! You can link your VIVO profile to as many web sites of interest as you wish.</p>

			<h2><strong>Can students be included in VIVO?</strong></h2>

				<p>Yes! Any student who asks to be in VIVO will be added to VIVO. Interested students should send a request to <a href="mailto:vivo@uflib.ufl.edu">vivo@uflib.ufl.edu</a>. </p>

			<h2><strong>What is the National Network?</strong></h2>

				<ul class="answers">
					<li>The national network of scientists includes a collection of sites providing information using the VIVO ontology, and tools which use the data to provide services to investigators.

					<li>Network participants include institutions with local installations of VIVO and those with research discovery and profiling applications that can provide Semantic Web-compliant data using the VIVO ontology.

					<li>The information accessible through the network's search and browse capability resides and is curated locally, within institutional VIVOs or other compatible Semantic Web applications.

				</ul>

			<h2><strong>Which institutions are currently participating in VIVO?</strong></h2>

				<ul class="answers">
					<li>The University of Florida, Cornell University, Indiana University, Washington University School of Medicine, The Scripps Research Institute, Weill Medical College, and Ponce Medical School are participating in the NIH award.

					<li>Collaborative VIVO projects are on-going at the University of Colorado, Northwestern University, Harvard University, Stonybrook University, the University of Pittsburgh, University of Nebraska, MIT, Brown University, the University of Pennsylvania, Woods Hole, Hunter College, the USDA, the NIH, the University of Chicago, the University of Buffalo, the University of Illinois Chicago, Oregon Health Sciences University, crossref.org, orcid.org, hubzero.org, the American Psychological Association, the American Academy for the Advancement of Science, the University of Leicester, the National Academy of Sciences in Beijing, and seven research universities in Australia.

					<li>More than a dozen other schools have Semantic Web applications that are compatible with the VIVO ontology and the national network. Some of these schools include Harvard, UCSF, the Medical University of South Carolina, Charles Drew University, and the University of Minnesota.

					<li>Thousands of inquiries and expressions of interest have come from additional institutions around the world.
					
				</ul>

			<h2><strong>Can I search VIVO at other schools?</strong></h2>

